\begin_inset Formula $G_{E}=g_{E}\lambda_{E},\quad G_{I}=g_{I}\lambda_{I}$
\end_inset

, the effective membrane time constant take the simple form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{\tau_{Q}} & =g_{L}+G_{E}+G_{I}\\
\mu_{Q} & =\tau_{Q}(g_{L}V_{0}+G_{E}E_{E}+G_{E}E_{I})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{E},N_{I}$
\end_inset

 limit, the individual synaptic conductances do not scale, it is sufficient
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{E},g_{I}\ll1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is in contrast to the case with current synapses, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{E},a_{I}$
\end_inset

