\begin_layout Section
Extensions of the integrate-and-fire neuron
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finite synaptic time constants 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Effect of the synaptic time constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\text{s}}$
\end_inset

 may be approximated in the model by modeling the synaptic input as a 
\series bold
dynamical quantity
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{\text{m}}\frac{dv(t)}{dt}=-[v(t)-V_{0}]+R_{\text{m}}I_{\text{s}}(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Synaptic current 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\text{s}}(t)$
\end_inset

 obeys the Langevin equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{\text{s}}\frac{dI_{s}(t)}{dt}=-I_{\text{s}}(t)+\mu+\sigma\sqrt{2\tau_{\text{s}}}\xi(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is possible to write a Fokker-Planck equation for the probability density
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(v,I_{\text{s}},t)$
\end_inset

 (Brunel and Sergi 1998)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stationary solution can be obtained by expanding as a power series in the
 parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\sqrt{\tau_{\text{s}}/\tau_{\text{m}}}<1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In case of conductance synapses, finite synaptic time constants are introduced
 in an analogous fashion to current synapses 
